The paper discusses secure scheduling of transactions in a federated setting, which involves coordination mechanisms for ensuring reliability and consistency with persistent data. This suggests that the paper could belong to the categories of databases (cs.DB), cryptography and security (cs.CR), distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), and software engineering (cs.SE). Among these categories, cs.DB and cs.CR seem to be the most likely, as they directly relate to the core concepts of transactions and security.
